To find the symmetric difference of (A ∆ B) ∆ A, we first need to find the symmetric difference of A and B, which is denoted as A ∆ B. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection.

A ∆ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B)

A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4} (union of A and B)
A ∩ B = {2, 3} (intersection of A and B)

A ∆ B = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {2, 3} = {1, 4}

Now, we need to find the symmetric difference of (A ∆ B) and A:

(A ∆ B) ∆ A = ({1, 4} ∪ A) - ({1, 4} ∩ A)

{1, 4} ∪ A = {1, 2, 3, 4}
{1, 4} ∩ A = {1}

(A ∆ B) ∆ A = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {1} = {2, 3, 4}

So, the symmetric difference of (A ∆ B) ∆ A is {2, 3, 4}.
